  <p>
    Smell is one of the earliest and most honest signals a septic system gives. The trouble is that
    "it smells like septic" can mean several very different things, from a harmless dried-out drain to
    a field in real distress. The key is to treat the odor as information: where you notice it, and
    when, narrows the possibilities considerably.
  </p>

  {/* Intended asset: /images/resources/why-septic-systems-produce-odors-hero.webp — see public/images/resources/README.md */}
