  <h2>A Little About the Gases</h2>
  <p>
    A working septic system produces gases as bacteria break down waste — that's normal and expected.
    In a healthy setup those gases are contained in the tank and vented safely up through the home's
    plumbing vent stack, well above where anyone would notice them. You smell a problem when that
    containment or venting breaks down somewhere, so the question is always: where is the gas escaping,
    and why?
  </p>

  <h2>Indoor Odors</h2>
  <p>
    A smell inside the house often has a plumbing explanation before a septic one. The most common and
    easily fixed cause is a drain trap that has dried out — a floor drain, a guest bathroom, or a
    seldom-used sink whose water seal has evaporated, letting sewer gas drift up. Running water to
    refill the trap frequently solves it. Venting issues, where the plumbing vents that balance air
    pressure aren't working properly, can also let odors into the home. If simple fixes don't resolve
    a persistent indoor smell, it can point to the system not moving waste along as it should, which
    is worth having checked.
  </p>

  <h2>Outdoor Odors — Near the Tank or Over the Field</h2>
  <p>
    A smell outside tends to be more telling. An odor concentrated near the tank or its lids can point
    to the tank or its access. An odor over the drain field — especially alongside soggy ground or
    unusually lush grass — can suggest the field is struggling to absorb and treat wastewater, which
    is a more significant issue. Our guide on
    <a href="/signs-of-drain-field-trouble/">signs of drain-field trouble</a> covers those clues in
    depth. Outdoor septic odors generally warrant an evaluation rather than a wait-and-see approach.
  </p>

  <h2>When an Odor Is an Early Warning</h2>
  <p>
    Because the same smell can have very different causes, an odor is best read as a prompt to
    investigate — and it's especially worth acting on when it arrives with company. A smell together
    with slow drains, gurgling, or wet spots over the field is the system telling you something is
    developing, and catching it early is far cheaper than waiting for a backup. Our overview of
    <a href="/resources/septic-problems/">septic warning signs</a> shows how these symptoms fit
    together.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Do</h2>
  <p>
    Start with the simple indoor checks — refill unused drain traps and see whether an indoor smell
    clears. For anything persistent, or any odor outdoors over the tank or field, have the cause
    identified rather than masked. <a href="/request-service/">Request septic service</a> and note
    where and when you notice the odor and any other symptoms; those details help a provider pinpoint
    it quickly.
  </p>
